### 3. Update Event Publication and Handling

With the default behavior of `std::priority_queue`, the highest priority event will always be at the front of the queue. Thus, your `Update` method actually simplifies as you don't need to sort the events yourself; they are automatically sorted upon insertion due to the priority queue's properties.

The modified `Update` method from your snippet doesn't need significant changes—just ensure you are using the correct method to remove elements from a `std::priority_queue`, which is `.top()` for accessing the next element and `.pop()` to remove it:

```cpp
void EventManager::Update() {
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(queueMutex);
    while (!eventQueue.empty()) {
        auto event = eventQueue.top(); // Use .top() instead of .front()
        eventQueue.pop(); // Removes the highest-priority element

        std::type_index typeIndex = std::type_index(typeid(*event));
        auto& handlers = subscribers[typeIndex];

        for (auto& handle : handlers) {
            handle(event);
        }
    }
}
```

### Note
This implementation assumes all events derive from a common `Event` base class that includes the `GetPriority()` method for retrieving an event's priority. You'll need to ensure that every event type provides its priority value according to your game's logic. This setup allows your event system to process events in order of priority, ensuring higher-priority events are handled first.
